did.abstract:
This collection contains reporters notebooks, handwritten notes, correspondence, audio recordings, drafts, articles, and photographs relating to the work life of journalist Trude B. Feldman. The records span circa 1941 through circa 2013. Trude B. Feldman (1924- ) was a journalist and former member of both the White House and the State Department Press Corps. She wrote most regularly for McCall's and Ladies Home Journal, but has also been published in The New York Times, Washington Post and Wall Street Journal. Feldman interview every US president from Lyndon Johnson to George W. Bush and many vice presidents as well. In addition she interviewed every secetary of state from Dean Rusk to Colin Powell. Feldman has also extensively covered the Mideast especially Israel. One of her first reporting assignments was complete coverage and reporting on the 122 sessions of the trial of Adolph Eichmann in Jerusalem.
Series one, two, five and eight are processed. The remainder of the collection is unprocessed and within each series there is almost no order. This collection will take more time to use. Please see staff for assistance.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This collection contains reporters notebooks, handwritten notes, correspondence, audio recordings, drafts, articles, and photographs relating to the work life of journalist Trude B. Feldman. The records span circa 1941 through circa 2013.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Trude B. Feldman (1924- ) was a journalist and former member of both the White House and the State Department Press Corps. She wrote most regularly for McCall's and Ladies Home Journal, but has also been published in The New York Times, Washington Post and Wall Street Journal. Feldman interview every US president from Lyndon Johnson to George W. Bush and many vice presidents as well. In addition she interviewed every secretary of state from Dean Rusk to Colin Powell. Feldman has also extensively covered the Mideast especially Israel. One of her first reporting assignments was complete coverage and reporting on the 122 sessions of the trial of Adolph Eichmann in Jerusalem.
Feldman was born August 13, 1924 and grew up in Hollywood California.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Arranged chronologically by year. Unknown dates are grouped together towards the end of the series.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains correspondence to and from freelance journalist Trude Feldman from the years Circa 1959-2013. As a correspondent to the White House, these correspondence include notable people such as, George W. Bush, George H.W. Bush, Barbara Bush, Eleanor Roosevelt, President and Mrs. Ford, President and Mrs. Carter, President Clinton, Secretary Clinton, President and Nancy Reagan, Harry Truman, Tipper Gore, Robert Kennedy and many others. In addition to these correspondence, there are many letters to and from multiple publishing companies.

odd.head: General
odd.p: Donor designated boxes 12, 19, 48 as having reporters notebooks. These are all boxes with the UP designation.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains notebooks, diaries, address books and appointment books from Trude Feldman. The documents date between 1941-2012. The notebooks contain interview notes from Feldman's time as a White House correspondant. Among the interview notes are more personal diary entries.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: In this series planners and notebooks were separated and then sorted by date. Any undated content are at the end of the series.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains a small sample of the drafts written by Trude Feldman during her time as a journalist. These records are dated from 1960-1968.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Series four contains three subseries: Newspaper articles, Magazine articles, and drafts. This series contains a selection of articles, and drafts for articles, from a variety of newspapers and magazines that Trude Feldman contributed during her long career.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Arranged into three subseries: Newspaper articles, Magazine articles and drafts.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains a selection of articles from between 1959-2007. Some newspapers that are included in this series are the Philadelphia Inquirer, the Washington Post, the Sacramento Bee and many more. This series also contains a large number of articles from Jewish publications and a few German newspapers.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains magazine articles written by Trude Feldman. Most of the articles come from McCall's Magazine and Ladies Home Journal from the years betwenn 1964-1999.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains draft material for future articles, correspondence, government documents and photographs. The materials date between 1941-2007. The bulk of the material is from the 1960s to 2000s.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains audiotapes, audiocassettes and VHS tapes containing interviews and speeches recorded by Trude Feldman. While a White House correspondent, Feldman recorded interviews and speeches given by former presidents, prime ministers, world leaders and Hollywood stars. The dates of the tapes are approximately 1964 to 2004. Some notable names include Presidents Bush, Clinton, Reagan, Nixon, Carter, Kennedy, Truman, Princess Margaret, Debbie Reynolds and Danny Kaye.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: This collection is described at the level with the items arranged alphabetically by the most prominent name on the item. Please note that some items do contain more than one interivew and not all the names are recorded in the description.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The tapes are arranged by type of media and then alphabetically by last name or theme if there is no name.
These themes include: Washington Conference on World Peace Through Law (1-3), Holocaust, Palestinian and Israeli Elections, and Peacekeepers to Bosnia.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This box contains three smaller boxes with audio cassettes of recordings done by Trude Feldman.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This box contains three smaller boxes and 1 folder of audio cassettes. These were recorded by Trude Feldman.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Box 37 is a selection of handwritten notes that were mixed in with Series 4 of this collection. The notes mostly pertain to her time as a White House correspondent.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains photographs of political and entertainment industry people that Trude Feldman interviewed for her work as a journalist. Most if not all of the images are official White House or other government or news agency images.

did.langmaterial: Series contains materials written in English, German, and Hebrew.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Arrangement maintained the original order from the donor, but that order does not appear to have been any true order to these records.
Boxes 31-32 are ordered by the court document number. Other documents retain original order.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains historical materials from the years 1961-1965 pertaining to Feldman's coverage of the Adolf Eichmann trial in Israel. Series contains specific materials relating to Feldman's interviews with Eichmann, Eichmann's defense lawyer, Dr. Robert Servatius, and Eichmann's wife, Veronika Liebl. Also included in the materials are drafts of articles Feldman published during and after the trial and drafts of chapters of a book she planned to publish. In addition, there are many audio recordings about the trial. Finally, there are reserach materials such as newspaper articles from the trial and personal corespondences between Feldman and others concerning her work in Germany and Israel.
